{
  "doc_id": "929",
  "text": "[4] Methyl chloride is less reactive with OH radicals, but makes an important contribution to organic chlorine in the stratosphere [CITATION_1] . This gas, which is emitted by biomass burning and natural sources, contributed approximately 15% of the total stratospheric organic chlorine in 1992 [CITATION_2] . Because of the emission reduction of anthropogenic halocarbons such as chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), the relative importance of methyl chloride as a stratospheric chlorine source is slowly increasing [CITATION_3] . In spite of numerous studies of the large-scale distribution of NMHC and methyl chloride, little is still known about their global trends [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
